Speakers (by percentage of participation):
Antonio (39%), Carl (24%), Kimutai (17%), ERICK (12%), Phil (4%), Francis (3%), Speaker 1 (1%), Speaker 2 (<1%)

Highlights & Key Details:

Antonio welcomed everyone to the Hackathon Info Session, emphasizing both the opportunity to contribute to Chamaconnect and the value of engaging with innovation, blockchain, and AI within the FinTech space. The event is organized by We Are Limited together with Salamander, aiming to give the community a chance to test, provide feedback, and find bugs before product launch. Participation is expected to not only help improve the application but also showcase individual skills and innovation.

ERICK, the project manager, highlighted the importance of thoroughly understanding the shared documentation, as submissions will be evaluated based on clarity and impact. Participation in the hackathon equates to becoming part of the Chamaconnect system. Clear, objective, and well-documented feedback is key.

Carl, from the technical team, underlined the focus areas:
- Technical depth in bug identification and proposals
- Innovation and impact of suggested features or enhancements
- Solutions should address real problems (e.g., fraud prevention, automated records, complex calculations)
- Submissions must work as described and include complete documentation
- Technical proposals should clearly explain both the problem and the rationale behind the solution

Technical Stack & Innovation:
- There is no restriction on the tech stack; choose technologies that best fit your proposed solution, but avoid unnecessary complexity.
- Innovations should be FinTech-related and directly improve or extend Chamaconnect for chamas, SACCOs, or group/stable banking.
- Primary objective: find and document bugs as clearly as possible, then propose feasible technical solutions.

Submission Guidelines:
- This is essentially a bug bounty — find, document, and suggest fixes for as many relevant issues as you can.
- Use a format similar to GitHub issues:
  1. Explain what you attempted
  2. Specify your environment (e.g., device, OS)
  3. List clear, step-by-step instructions to reproduce the bug
  4. Provide screenshots when relevant
  5. Suggest possible causes and solutions
- Proposals should be submitted as a single PDF, with bugs as the primary section and any innovation/feature suggestions as an optional second section.
- You must set up an account, interact with the platform, and clearly identify and address usability, performance, or functionality issues.
- Submissions should include:
  - Problem statement & root cause
  - Proposed solution & technical approach (with public GitHub link if code is provided)
  - Expected impact
  - A clean, well-structured repo with comprehensive documentation (README) for any code submissions

Participation & Questions:
- Participation is individual (no teams); each participant should create their own Chamaconnect account for testing.
- The more issues/features you identify and address, the stronger your submission.
- Judges will assess submissions based on the quantity and quality of identified bugs, clarity of documentation, and effectiveness of proposed solutions.
- If you have already worked on solutions, make sure to follow the new structured format for submission.
- Support is available via WhatsApp and support@temaconnect.io for any clarifications.

Timeline:
- All submissions must be made by Sunday, 11:59pm, as stated in the official communications.
- Use the time effectively to thoroughly test, document, and propose your solutions.

The session closed with a Q&A, reiterating openness to further questions up to the deadline, and encouraging concise, well-structured, and impactful proposals.


